!wd begin
quasi-bot BOT 11/12/2022 8:21 PM
This event will involve a lot of bot commands and exploration. Use bot commands to explore your surroundings, and find small quests for rewards. You can explore an area, look at objects, or interact with objects using the command for the area. ex: <pf> is the command for the petrified forest area, and if you wish to look at a gnarled tree, you'd type <!pf gnarled tree> to do so. Actions to take or things to look at will most often required one-three words, and will never require more than four words. If you discover a quest, do a short rp relating to that quest. You are free to rp ANY of the involved npcs to facilitate this.

quasi-bot BOT 11/15/2022 6:54 PM
The figure smiles and waves at you, and you recognize them from the merchant's caravan. They're a scientific type named Nashara. "Hello!" they say. "Curious to see what I'm doing here? To tell the truth, I'm looking at ancient bones. Want to see?" They gesture at the massive bones of some creature that almost seems to have melded with the rock. "Fascinating right?" They say. "This isn't the first set like them that I've found either. Every time we come here for trade, I manage to extract different skeletons. You want to know the weird thing? None of them are creatures that exist in Triem Sha, or even Tiranthe as far as I can tell, and even weirder is that they aren't even the same as each other. A lot of them are huge too. I want to write a paper about them and submit it to Senyan University, but I'd like to hear other theories before settling on one of my own. What do you think they are, and why do you think they're here?" QUEST DISCOVERED: I Call it Paleontology: A scientist named Nashara says that in this section of the Triem Sha desert, many odd ancient bones can be found. They insist that the bones belong to no creature that currently exists in Triem Sha, and that every set of bones belongs to a unique creature. But why might this be? They want to hear your theory on the matter and get ideas for a paper theyll send to Senyan University. "Well, have you considered that maybe such creatures come from the sea?" He offers in thought. "Got washed up, wandered around the desert 'til they got lost and dried up? I don't know, maybe the university can confirm that-- I'm sure they're plenty knowledgeable about the sea and what dwells in there." Considering that he was a merman, he should know, but he frankly does not care. "If not, maybe they're like... old, ancient creatures. Look at fairy tales maybe. See if anything there matches with this. Maybe that's where writers got their inspiration from." With a shrug, he asks the scientist here the nearest settlement was and he points at a certain direction, which Vasil ends up following. He doesn't see anything but he'll just follow the dude for now.

The old man has black scales scattered across his leathery skin, and his brown eyes glimmer with hope when he sees you. He roughly grabs the shoulders of someone in your party with a strong, wiry grip. "Hello!" he says. I fear going too much deeper in-- I'm not as young as I once was, but if you can find the cave in my place, we could split the treasure." He holds up a gold ring. It glimmers in the light, and jingles as it moves."This here should guide you to the location. The ornaments dangling from it point the way. Remember to follow its instructions very carefully, and once you find the puzzle it reveals, bring it back to me." QUEST DISCOVERED: A Diamond in the Rough: Kooky old merchant Jvoseuh keeps muttering day in and day out about a hidden cave of treasures in the desert, but nobody believes him. He grabs you by the shoulders and implores you to find it with this golden ring and bring him the puzzle within. The dangling ornaments on it will point towards the cave. Using the <!wd goldring> command, you will wander the desert until you find the spot and then use the words the ring will reveal to you there. The pale twisting cliffs are... well... exactly that. They stretch to the sky in odd formations, and their stone is white and chalky. Jagged formations jut from their sides, sharp and curving like the teeth of a carnivorous beast. It appears this will be a difficult climb. OOC: Roll a phys success of 3 or higher to successfully retrieve a bundle of Lanti Grass. If you roll 2 successes, you get fairly high, but end up falling. Lose 2 VIT (3 if flying, as the jagged cliffs pierce you before you get make your way up.). If you roll 1 success, you don't go as far. Lose 1 VIT. (2 if flying, as the jagged cliffs pierce you). If someone in your party rolls 2 LORE successes, roll phys to climb with advantage. (roll twice, and take the higher result). If someone in your party rolls 1 ACA success to investigate for Lanti Grass, then when you successfully make the climb, get 2 bundles instead of one.

If the party member on lookout duty rolls 1 success in lore or academics, the character climbing can jump to safety in time. If not, then the character climbing loses one VIT. !wd tallest twisting cliffs
quasi-bot BOT 12/05/2022 6:52 PM
The jagged cliffs stretch into the sky like twisted fingers. The sun shines against them, painfully bright. The nsiona fruits are likely at the top, but it seems like a dangerous climb. OOC: Your OC can use whatever means to get to the top, be it flying, magic, or climbing. All they require is 2 successes in the related stat. If the roll fails, lose one VIT from the fall. Roll a 1d6 to see how many fruit are found atop the cliff. If there aren't enough, another cliff must be ascended. For every cliff ascended, flip a coin. If the coin is on heads, the fruit is harvested without issue. If the coin is tails, a young roc swoops down to claw at you. Damage can be avoided by a party member on lookout duty. If the party member on lookout duty rolls 1 success in lore or academics, the character climbing can jump to safety in time. If not, then the character climbing loses one VIT. If the character climbing is KO'd, then this quest fails, and another will be needed to be taken from Ahmudia to receive the bead.
